  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Prayer at the Yellow Register Altar
  author: Choi Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: 'I petition according to the proper rites and ceremonies. Though my body remains entangled in the affairs of this world, my spirit yearns for the Way of Truth. The supreme Way is shrouded in mystery—beyond all form and perception—yet when the heart is sufficiently devoted and sincere, there must come a resonance, a response. Thus do I constantly burn incense and practice discipline, unwilling to waste even a moment. I aspire to learn from the sea until I merge with its vastness, to cherish the dragon so that I need not fear the true dragon. I do not seek the praise of noble names, but only to embody the spirit of diligent practice. Yet having been entrusted early with the seal of Prime Minister and long wielded the authority of the Ministry of War, I have stood at crossroads of danger and disorder, undertaking campaigns against the corrupt and treacherous. With great concern I fear that in matters of governance and law, errors may have accumulated in the celestial records, and misdeeds may be inscribed upon the dark ledger, inescapable and without remedy. Now the spring season passes away while the heat of summer rises strong. I bow my head to heaven and offer my heart to earth, standing humbly to present these humble offerings and prayers. I beseech the Three Honored Ones of the Highest and all the sages of the ten directions: look with compassion upon this sincere heart and bestow your boundless mercy. May a thousand calamities dissolve like lightning, and a hundred blessings descend like clouds. May I forever rely upon your spiritual grace, that my roots may flourish and grow. Let the dust beyond the threshold be swept away, that my labors may bear fruit early. Let me glimpse again the sun and moon within the vessel, freed from the burden of anxious dreams. I, your servant, repent of my faults and humbly beg for grace, my heart trembling with reverent awe. I respectfully submit this prayer.'
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Yellow Register' (黃籙) refers to a Daoist religious ceremony meant to purify karma and seek divine protection.
  - key: ''
    value: '''Learning from the sea'' and ''the true dragon'' are allusions to spiritual cultivation—progressing from lesser to greater understanding, moving beyond fear to enlightenment.'
  - key: ''
    value: Choi Chi-won held high positions in the Silla court as Prime Minister (相印) and had authority over military affairs (兵符), making this petition a personal plea for absolution from potential governmental missteps.
  - key: ''
    value: '''Celestial records'' and ''dark ledger'' represent the cosmic accounting of human deeds in Daoist and Buddhist cosmology.'
